The number of patients treated for exposure to the unknown nerve agent in the British town of Salisbury has risen to 21. But officials have not yet confirmed exactly what substance they found. Here are the top five substances political regimes have used in the past - or may use - to kill people - adversaries or traitors. Investigators at work, after Russian agents poisoned defector Litwinienko in London Polonium 210 Russian agents used the radioactive element to poison former FSB agent Alexander Litvinenko in London in 2006, British investigators say. Former Russian spy-colleagues met him there and poured the substance into his tea. It took 23 days between the day when he was hospitalized and his death. The substance has a half life of 138 days. It is almost impossible to detect if the investigation starts too late. However, the main reason why many investigators may fail to detect it is that they simply don't look for it. Polonium can not be bought on the market. In nature, it only appears in marginal quantities as a product of radioactive decay. Only nuclear powers are able to produce Polonium in quantities that could be used to kill. In order to produce the lethal dose of 100 nanograms, one would need several hundred kilograms of raw uranium ore. In a nuclear reactor, one could generate Polonium by bombarding bismuth with neutrons. Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
